Section Summary: In 1538, King Henry VIII issued a writ summoning Thomas Becket, the long-dead Archbishop of Canterbury, to appear before him, and when he didn't, his shrine was destroyed and his name was erased from records. However, this didn't mark the end of pilgrimages to Canterbury, as a new wave of enthusiasm for the site emerged in the 20th century. Many modern pilgrims take the train to Canterbury, but those who walk the old Pilgrims' Way from Winchester are rewarded with a richer experience and a gradual unfolding of the city's story. The city of Canterbury has a long history dating back to the Palaeolithic Age, with the Romans establishing a settlement there, which they called Durovernum, and later the Anglo-Saxons rebuilding the town and renaming it Cantwarabyrig. The city's strategic location at the junction of several Roman roads made it an important center, and it eventually became the capital of Kent under the reign of Ethelbert in 561.
