Section section_02 (Chars 8656–12872):
Section Summary: Ethelbert, the king of Kent, had extended his power beyond Kent and had authority as far north as the Humber, with Canterbury as the metropolis of his dominions. Prior to 597, Canterbury was a heathen city, except for the influence of Ethelbert's Frankish wife Bertha and her chaplain Bishop Luidhard, who had introduced Christianity. In 597, Augustine arrived and was allowed to preach and instruct the people, leading to many conversions, including Ethelbert's own baptism. Canterbury became the headquarters of the Christian Church in England, a position it has held for over 1,300 years, and remains a significant ecclesiastical center to this day. The old church of St. Martin's, where Augustine and his monks began to preach, is considered a unique and historic site, although its exact origins and age are still a matter of debate among archaeologists and antiquaries.
